be a man of honour in eighteenth and nineteenth century England. A thorough survey of the incidence and distribution of duelling, both socially and geographically, identifies those sub-groups of gentlemen most likely to duel. The author considers the mores and manners of such groups and asks why it was that within specific professions, minor slightscould only be requited by a demand for satisfaction. In doing so, the author rejects those traditional histories of duelling which have failed to engage with the internal dynamics and internal logic of the phenomenon itself.Too often historians have explained the rise of opposition to duelling in terms of social and cultural change whilst at the same time treating the duel as though its ideological content had become irrevocably fixed in the early seventeenth century. Honour culture too had a social and an intellectual history and the author outlines those conflicts of ideas within the culture of honour itself that did much to hasten the demise of the English duel. A Polite Exchange of Bullets will be welcomed as a fresh approach to an important social phenomenon by all those interested in duelling and in English social and cultural history. STEPHEN BANKS is a lecturer in criminal law at Reading University Law School and co-director of The Forum of Legal and Historical Research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDuelingxHistoryy18th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aDuelingxHistoryy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aHonorxSocial aspectsxHistoryy18th century. 0aHonorxSocial aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aCultural History.  aDuel.  aEighteenth Century.  aEnglish Gentleman.  aHonor Culture.  aHonor.  aIdeological Stage.  aManners.  aMores.  aNineteenth Century.  